  "local_port": 45450,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How does GST Bill will work?",
  "response": "The GST (Goods and Services Tax) Bill is a comprehensive indirect tax on the manufacture, sale, and consumption of goods and services throughout India. The bill aims to replace multiple indirect taxes imposed by the central and state governments with a unified tax system, making it easier to do business and increasing transparency in the tax system. Here's how the GST Bill works:\n\n1. Dual GST structure: The GST system consists of two components - the Central GST (CGST) levied by the central government and the State GST (SGST) levied by the state governments. Both taxes are applicable on the same taxable transaction, but collected by the respective authorities.\n\n2. GST rates: The GST Council, consisting of the central and state finance ministers, determines the GST rates for various goods and services. There are multiple GST slabs - 0%, 5%, 12%, 18%, and 28%, with essential items attracting lower rates and luxury items attracting higher rates.\n\n3. Input Tax Credit: GST allows for seamless flow of input tax credit (ITC) across the supply chain, which means businesses can claim credit for the GST paid on inputs (purchases) against the GST liability on outputs (sales). This helps to eliminate the cascading effect of taxes and reduces the overall tax burden on businesses.\n\n4. Registration: Businesses with an annual turnover above a specified threshold need to register for GST. Once registered, they are required to file regular returns and pay the applicable GST.\n\n5. IGST for inter-state transactions: For inter-state transactions, the Integrated GST (IGST) is levied, which is a combination of CGST and SGST. The revenue collected under IGST is shared between the central and state governments.\n\n6. GSTN: The Goods and Services Tax Network (GSTN) is a non-profit organization that provides the IT infrastructure for the GST system. It facilitates registration, return filing, and payment processes for taxpayers.\n\n7. Composition Scheme: Small businesses with a turnover below a specified limit can opt for the Composition Scheme, under which they pay a fixed percentage of their turnover as GST and follow simpler compliance requirements.\n\nIn summary, the GST Bill aims to create a more efficient, transparent, and business-friendly tax system in India by replacing multiple indirect taxes with a unified tax structure.",
